<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="348" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="47" pageNumber="348">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,188,213]" pageId="47" pageNumber="348">Discussion.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Molineri" box="[340,674,188,213]" pageId="47" pageNumber="348" refString="Molineri, C. &amp; Emmerich, D. (2010) New species and new stage descriptions of Campsurus major species-group (Polymitarcyidae, Campsurinae), with first report of silk-case construction in a mayfly nymphs. Aquatic Insects, 32, 265 - 280." type="journal article" year="2010">Molineri &amp; Emmerich (2010)</bibRefCitation>
described and diagnosed the species based only on males. We here give the first description of the female adult, but nymphs remain unknown. The female morphology of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Molineri &amp; Emmerich ." authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amapaensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="348">C. amapaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
coincides with that of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Needham &amp; Murphy" authorityYear="1924" box="[586,653,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis box="[586,653,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="348">major</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Molineri" box="[970,1308,260,285]" pageId="47" pageNumber="348" refString="Molineri, C. &amp; Emmerich, D. (2010) New species and new stage descriptions of Campsurus major species-group (Polymitarcyidae, Campsurinae), with first report of silk-case construction in a mayfly nymphs. Aquatic Insects, 32, 265 - 280." type="journal article" year="2010">Molineri &amp; Emmerich (2010)</bibRefCitation>
, but it may be separated from the other known females of this group (
<taxonomicName authority="Esben-Petersen 1912" authorityName="Esben-Petersen" authorityYear="1912" box="[855,1266,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentinus">
<emphasis box="[855,1012,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="348">C. argentinus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Esben-Petersen" box="[1025,1266,295,320]" pageId="47" pageNumber="348" refString="Esben-Petersen, T. (1912) New and little-known species of Ephemerida from Argentine (Neuropt.). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift, 1912, 333 - 342." type="journal article" year="1912">Esben-Petersen 1912</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Needham &amp; Murphy 1924" authorityName="Needham &amp; Murphy" authorityYear="1924" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis box="[1331,1436,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="348">C. major</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Needham" box="[151,453,332,357]" pageId="47" pageNumber="348" refString="Needham, J. G. &amp; Murphy, H. E. (1924) Neotropical mayflies. Bulletin of the Lloyd Library, 22, 1 - 79." type="journal article" year="1924">Needham &amp; Murphy 1924</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) by the smaller size and darker coloration of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Molineri &amp; Emmerich ." authorityYear="2010" box="[974,1141,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="348" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amapaensis">
<emphasis box="[974,1141,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="348">C. amapaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and also by details of the female sockets (
<figureCitation box="[332,430,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="348">Fig. 145</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
